description.text:
This is a variation of thingiverse.com/thing:11657
I decided to use LM8UU linear bearings simply because I could not find the recommended nylon washers and although I tested some replacement options for the nylon bushings I could not help wanting to utilize linear bearings. After trying a few options I settled for some LME8UUAJ Adjustable Ball Bushings.
I had this version laser cut to test the idea. 4 holes over each of the bearing holes were drilled (shown in the pic) and were tapped with 2mm threads for the grub screws to hold the linear bearings.
And another option for bearings...
I decided to try Spherical Bushings(GE-08.00x16.00W300) after noticing that the LM8 bearings were a little noisy. The Spherical bushings are self aligning, which maeks the job of assembly/alignment very easy, and they are of course very quiet. I hace included some extra photos for referecne.

1) Cut the Table support as per the attached drawing.
2) Drill holes for 2mm (or 2.5mm) grub screws over each of the LM8UU linear bearing holes.
3) Tap the holes for the grub screws.
4) When tightening the screws you will need to ensure the bearings are alinged as you tighten. So feed the rod through the bearings first, then tighten each a little ensuring the rod can travel easily.

description.text: Thanks to its metal frame, the Printrbot Simple is a sturdy and reliable 3D printer perfect for rapid prototyping. One downside to this is the lack of traction when it is on solid surfaces, and fast prints can cause a lot of sliding. Without a way to secure the machine, it could interfere with other equipment or fall to cause a range of problems. Tilting is another issue with the Simple, especially if filament is mounted on a spool rack and the X-Axis Upgrade is installed. Adding "Printr Feet" to the frame prevents both of these issues, while also providing more air flow to the motherboard!

title: GoPro Mag Mount
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
A friend wanted a mount for his GoPro so he could mount his GoPro to his car or truck and do automotive videos with the camera at different locations outside his car. He had only found a suction cup based one and was worried he would send his expensive GoPro down the road. He asked me to come up with a design that could be easily attached to the car or truck and be put on any part of it. With much thinking I came up with this. It's a magnetic base mount. I used 4 Neodymium Rare Earth Magnets (which have a 13lb pulling force) at the four corners and arranged it so the cross has a leading leg in front and behind the camera to counter lifting. It can be used on any steel part of the body as long as the curve of the body isn't too much to not allow contact of the magnets on all four sides. Was considering lifting the center up but that would allow air under the mount and decided against it.

Since the pictures I have added a very thin layer of spray on Plasti Dip to the bottom of the mount to keep it from scratching the paint and also keep it from being able to slide on the smooth surface of the paint. There is a link below for the magnets I ordered and used. I simply epoxied them in place. This mount has seen speeds of 100+ without moving.

ATTENTION: I am not responsible for any damage to your camera or car/truck by using this camera mount. This works for me and my friend so I thought I would share it on here.

You can reverse the pin 7 to pin 44 at your convenience, it depends of the connector you used for your fans

title: X Carriage Mod for 3/8" Rod and Bearing for HyperCube 3D Printer

description.text:
Modify the diameter of parts associated with 10mm anodized aluminum tube to be the 3/8" (9.525mm) tube/rod dimension. 10mm anodized aluminum tube is difficult to find in the US. 3/8" parts are available from at least these sources.

Tube (come in 6 foot): https://www.mcmaster.com/#catalog/122/3705/=15ddz7c
Rod not anodized comes in 3 foot: https://www.lowes.com/pd/Steelworks-3-ft-x-3-8-in-Aluminum-Metal-Round/3053651

Bearing: (IDxODxLength is 3/8"x1/2"x1")
https://www.mcmaster.com/#9368t22/=15g722l
https://www.mcmaster.com/#1688k13/=15g763j

(Note. McMaster will quote you shipping after you placed an order and in my case, $14 for the tube and $4 for the four bearing but I ordered separately)

You will need to print 2 of each STL files. Two of 360mm rod/tube and 4 bearing. These will replace the original X carriage parts related to to 10mm rod (XY_Joiner and Dual_bushing_holder).

I am in the middle of a build also so although I am confident these changes are good but I can't be 100% sure. Let me know if you spot my mistakes.

[Update Dec-8-2016] Tested the design and the combined X carriage is not gliding down smooth. I will make changes to the design so don't print these files just yet. Sorry to come up with premature design but my parts are finally coming in so that I can begin testing.

{Update Dec-9-2016} Adjusted the distance for the two rods on XY_Joiner and widen the dual bushing somewhat. The gliding is smooth now. I think the gliding will never be as frictionless as using LM8UU bearings. But that's not the point in the original HyperCube design anyway. The X Carriage now slides with consistent friction, without binding and much quieter than LM8UU bearing. In the photo, you will notice I used 3 bearing because I found using only 3, the friction is less and I detect no play.

[Update Dec-18-2016] Added XY_Joiner_for38_V1.1.stl for double LM8UU bearing option. See Tech2C's Hypercube 3D Printer Build Log #14 for explanation. This correspond to XY_Joiner_V1.1 but modified for 3/8" rod. You also need to print XY_Clamp_V1.1 in the thingiverse Hypecube 3D Printer's page for the opposite side of the double bearing.

description.text:
This project came about thanks to information posted by members of the 3drpilots forum. Information and source for most of the electronics required for this build can be found at Grant Conery's excellent Instructables write-up -- http://www.instructables.com/id/GM-Multi-Solo-Charger/. His multi-charger build is also here - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1496497

As I don't go through very many packs when I fly, I went with a dual charger setup. Having a 200 x 200 mm print bed also dictated the maximum dimensions for the project.

I have a bunch of 2.5 mm self-tapping screws in various lengths so most of the internal components are held in with those. The terminal strip and the feet/cover plate are M3 screws. The housing is printed in PLA. I found that it holds threads very well if you start by using a tap for the first few millimeters and then just using the screw with a touch of lubricant on it.

The bi-color LED from the converter was removed and relocated in the case. Actually, the LEDs were destroyed in the process of removal so replacements were installed. The wires from the converters have female servo connectors on them and plug right into the LED's legs.

The housing for the plug slides together and snaps in place. There's a tab with slots for zip-ties to serve as a strain relief. Zip-ties are probably not necessary if the plug is installed in the case but it's there.

Instead of trying to print holes and mounts in vertical surfaces, I made slots in the housing for a fan and an XT60 connector for power input. The XT60 connector snaps into the two halves and the assembly slides into the cutout. The fan mount works the same way. The fan is a 25 x 25 x 7 mm unit from Amain Hobbies -- https://www.amainhobbies.com/hobbywing-25x25x7mm-2507sh12v-esc-cooling-fan-hwa86080020/p349371. It's small but pushes(or pulls) a lot of air. I have it configured as an exhaust fan. It's pretty loud. The fan mounting plate should be a fairly tight fit in the housing or it'll rattle and be even noisier than it needs to be.

The terminal strip is a 8 circuit Molex - https://www.arrow.com/en/products/0387700408/molex

description.text:
It's the one missing feature: not backlighting, no reading in the dark.
This is a prototype of a solution: a sheet of clear acrylic that fits into the screen's bevel and another opaque sheet that covers it at the bottom (you only lose the page count that way, no text) and the upper corners. The idea is to add an LED in each corner (there is enough clearance between the opaque part and the reader's faceplate) to illuminate the beveled corners of the transparent part, which should become a waveguide.

This is a prototype / proof of concept, just to see if the clear acrylic piece would actually light the screen in a useful way. 
If it does, I would add mounts for the LEDs (altho... hot glueing them behind the opaque part would work too) and someplace to put the batteries.
If you have an idea on how to improve on this, it's under CC license, feel free to tinker!

title: Mendel X Carriage modified to hold BitsFomBytes hot end

description.text:
I own a rapman (bits from bytes laser cut reprap derivative) and looking at many designs I like the extruder this guys made very much. The extruder is divided in two parts (linked with 2 screws) - the "drive" part where a stepper driven shaft grab and push the filament - and the "hot end" part that is, well, melting the plastic.
After many kg's of filament (abs, pp, hdpe, pla) trough the hot end from bfb I never had issues with it and as they sold hot end as a separate "part" I figure one can mount it to the Mendel using the pinch wheel drive and the bowden cable as the "other part" of the extruder assembly. This is a good idea but a hot end from bfb is ~40mm in dia hence I had to modify the carriage a bit (just drilled a big 40mm hole in them).

• print lower carriage
  • print upper carriage
    • assemble as defined in mendel manual put the hot end trough the hole
    attach the "bowden cable holder" to the carriage and attach the bfb hot end to the holder (this part is still being drawn)

description.text:
Here is another variation of my gear phone case.
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:51560
It is a festive Christmas snowman! His green buttons and mittens are now the only thing he is wearing, because the wind blew his hat off.
The body of this case was made with Makerware's newer dual extrusion routine.
This is a multi-part print that is best served with ABS.

All parts are setup to print at .2mm thick slices. .1 will work, but is not necessary.
The STL files names start with the color you should print the parts. The head and body are multiple color parts that you will need to pause after .4mm (2 layers). Then purge and change your colors from green or black to white.
It is best to print all the gears and rivets with at least two sets on the plate, because the first one usually doesn't get a full first layer. The amount of plastic you waste is minimal. I print 3 sets at a time to make 2 complete cases.
The two parts for the case should be merged in Makerware, and printed as a dual extrusion. Load the white in the right extruder, because it prints first. The wind will not show up as well if you let the red print first. The order I printed the parts is:
Dual extrusion case
Green rivets
Green / White body gear
White small hand gears
Black hat rivet
Black / white head gear
Orange carrot rivet After you have all the parts, snap the rivets through the gears and into the case. They will be tight in the case! You may need to lay the rivets down on a table and push on the edges of the case from inside. Once you have all the gears in place, make sure the mittens, carrot, and hat are all facing the way you want. Use a mix of acetone and ABS to glue in the rivets from inside. Use two heavy coats. The phone slides in with the top first, then snap the bottom of the case around it. The gears will be a little stiff at first. Roll the hat gear on your pants, or a smooth fabric quickly back and forth. You will have them spinning freely in no time.

title: Printable Hobby Knife - Number 11 X-Acto Blade Size

description.text:
A serviceable printable hobby knife.

Update: 06/14/2017

I'm replacing the original files with this V2 version. The design has been modified to strengthen the fingers that hold the blade. Much more robust now. Also, I scrapped the cap design I had originally. The original cap design forced you to orient the blade a certain way to get the blade in. This new design can be put on in any orientation. The only drawback is that it doesn't socket onto the tip of the handle when not in use, but honestly I found that I never used that feature anyway (I doubt anyone else did either - it was just cumbersome). Note: the cap will be pretty tight when you first put it on, so BEFORE you put a blade in (for safety), screw on the collet as normal and then snap the cap on and off a few times. It will clearance itself and be a lot easier to use.

Update: 12/10/2016

I modified the cap design and how it snaps onto the handle (due to some feedback that the cap was cracking on some prints). This new version has no slots on the side, which is where the crack was forming. I also moved the retention dots down on the base so now instead of the cap snapping onto those, it uses those dots as a "stop". It is now totally an interference fit and uses the layer ridges as the friction surface for retention. I did a test of taking the new cap on and off about 200 times and after the first few, it didn't seem to develop any additional slop. Feedback appreciated!

I wanted a bunch of spare hobby knife handles to distribute through the various places in my shop, but none of the printable versions I found were very robust and tended to let the blade slip pretty badly under normal use (for me that is cutting foam board, balsa, and other lightweight material).

This design grips the blade from both the sides and the edge and has a detent inside the collet to help keep the blade from slipping out. Also, the collet shaft is thick enough so that there is a decreased danger of the knife breaking when you are applying pressure.

I also wanted it to be quick to make in its most basic form, so it is designed so that you can use a 3/8" dowel as a handle.

There is also printable handle which is designed to decrease the propensity for the knife to roll around, and also an optional cap. The cap sockets onto the end of the handle when not in use.

Obviously this is a printed hobby knife, so don't go bananas with it. It's strong, but not as strong metal one. Be careful.

title: Replicator Dual X Axis Cable Chain With Support Track

description.text:
This is my variation on an X axis cable management chain. I had the inevitable X motor cable failure, and I wanted a way to make this a more controllable area of my printer.
All the chains I found on Thingiverse either were too tight, let the cable bend too much, or had no support method for the chain.
Here is my variation on an overly abundant theme.

All these parts were meant to be printed without support or rafts.
I needed 12 links of the main chain part, 1 of each end, and 1 support track.
The top part screws to the X motor mount with a 10x3mm screw.
Train your wires where you want them and use a zip tie in the provided holes. Thread another zip tie through the support track and the bottom connector. Hold the support track where the chain just misses the Y motor with the gantry all the way against the Y limit switch. Drill 2 3mm holes for the track, and use 2 20x3mm screws and nuts on the inside. Now tighten the bottom zip tie, and add another on the lower track.

Preparing the Car body

There is a little bit of printing support in the car body to help stable printing. The three thin connected parts on the bottom of the frame should be removed before assembly. This can be done with a small (pre-heated) knife.

Assemble the body

To assemble you will need several nuts and bolts. We use four 4x12mm bolts to assemble the body. If you also want to assemble the extra's, you will sometimes need 4x16mm bolts.

The default frame consists out of:

  • 1_lightsensor_single
  • 1_medtcar_body
  • 1_tail_wheel
  • 1_pi_breadboard

We provided an assembly video to help the building proces.

OpenScad

The design is created in OpenScad, an open source coding based, 3D design program. This makes the design highly adjustable.

Programming Challenges

We used the robot cars to challenge students into programming with Python. We designed four challenges which use the sensors in different combinations. the challenges are based on 'real' developments in the field of autonomous cars:

  • Navigation (follow a line to get from A to B; is default challenge for camjam)
  • Google car (drive autonomously through a model-city without bumping into pedestrians or lanterns)
  • Merry-go-round (drive around an oval track within a specific timeframe)
  • Find the bright-spot (Create a search robot which can find a white spot on a dark floor)
Pimp your ride

The default robot car can be used to perform all the given challenges, but it's always nice to have an unique, optimised car. By clearing challenges, students receive virtual money to buy extra's. These extra's are also available and are:

  • Backpack (A module on the back of the car which can hold a custom 5volt battery pack)
  • Spoiler (A car can only go fast with a spoiler right?)
  • Planetail (Fly like a bird and convert your car to a driving plane)
  • Police lights (Add police lights and you will be noticed. This extra also creates an extra challenge, because students have to program it themselves. This is not provided in the camjam #3 set. You will need a red and blue 5mm led, 220Ohm resistor and some wiring)

title: Pre-assembled mechanical pull chain toy soldier

description.text: I always thought that the pull string toy soldier we had on our tree when I was a kid was pretty cool. For this contest, I decided to create a preassembled pull chain toy soldier. The mechanical interactions all print as one print with eleven mechanical joints plus a six segment chain. The only thing needed is to pop on the back plate and the hook. I have also included a pull string version if you don't like the chain. A really poor video of it in action can be found here: http://youtu.be/kHgTXPtbLq0 I made all of the joints loose at 1mm spacing to make it easier to print. Short (about 3-4mm) bridges are used to complete the joints. They are narrow and have enough room to sag that they should be doable for most printers. I created this using tinkercad. I have shared the designs in tinkercad so others can modify them. They are "Pull chain toy soldier" "Pull string toy soldier" "Toy soldier back and hook" and "Pull string ball". I'm working on making a Santa version that I will upload next.

All of the inner joints are functional when they come off the printer if it printed correctly.  The inner connecting rods were the only parts that did not want to stay put when I printed it, so I included a version with tiny cheater bars to hold them in place which can easily be cut away after printing.  Make sure that all of the joints move freely, straighten out the chain, pop on the back and hook and you're done.  I am painting mine with Acrylic paints to bring out the details.  I'll add a pic when its done.  
This print has many little pieces in it. To keep the pieces from coming off without a raft, I use a light misting of  aqua net extra super hold on my bed.  A light tap with a wood chisel easily knocks them loose.

description.text:
Simple 120mm fan mount using the outer radius of the center frame part under the fan hub. Checked for function on a few different generic PC 120mm cooling fans with 4mm plastic center frame thickness and 44mm outer diameter of that center frame part under the fan. I have seen some that will not work but most should (4 of 5 types in my fan bin work with it, one weird antec case fan with an open frame and no shroud will not clip in). Easy enough to print and verify with your fan as it won't cost much time or filament.

Mounting holes are 3.3mm for M3 screws. Mounting holes diameter is 54.75mm at 120 degrees offset radially.

This is part of a larger stepper motor duct for mini kossel sized Delta printers that will be released separately. Making a post for just this bracket since it is useful on its own or integrated into other designs.

The end of "Novembeard" reminded me of two things: how much I dislike facial hair and how not all double-edged razor blade packaging is alike. Case in point: The razors I do not like come in a fancy plastic dispensing case that also safely contains the spent blades. The razors I do like come in a cheap cardboard box with no safe way of disposing spent blades. So I did what any maker would do and designed my own disposal box for spent blades. This Spent Blade Box consists of two tight-fitting pieces. Slide your used razor into the slot and it's safely tucked away where it cannot lacerate the trash bag or fingers. The interior of the box features a little nub that helps prevent razors from sliding out (without a bit of manual and intentional bending action). OpenSCAD source files are included in the downloads, should you want to tweak the size or fit-tolerance.

Just print the two pieces, inner and outer. Since this is meant to be a solid box, but is also skeletal with its windows and slot, you may want to increase your infill value. Press the inner box into the outer box for a tight friction fit.

description.text:
photo on printbed shows previous version without reinforcement

While waiting for the delivery guy with our Makerspace's laser cutter, I made this fancy two color knob for the door leading to the machine. Although initially designed on a whim, it ended up being very sturdy after some slight alterations and I thought I'd share this model with you!

No dual extrusion required, but two M5 nuts and bolts - enjoy :-)

Rafts:

40 %

Notes:

I switched the color from yellow to black mid-print to recreate the look of a laser warning sign. With a machine and filament you are comfortable with, this is pretty easy! X3D file with color information is also included in case someone has dual extrusion.

Nuts & Bolts

Two M5 nuts that will just fit into the recesses in the base (heat them with a soldering iron if it is a little tight) and two M5 bolts going through the door from the inside are required in addition to the printed part. Make sure the bolts are long enough, I ended up sinking mine quite a bit into the door...

Designed with Tinkercad based on approx. measurements of a salt shaker that felt right and an imported SVG sketch of the laser warning symbol. The lack of a chamfer around the base is a little annoying, if the knob ever breaks or someone asks nicely I'll get back to working on this ;-)

title: Working Radio Ornament - Tune in to Studio 360 from your tree!

description.text: Build a working radio ornament for your tree and listen to public radio with the family!! As an avid NPR listener - formerly WNYC, now WBEZ is local in Chicago - I thought it would be fun to honor radio broadcasting in this ornament. It's designed to use the Sparkfun FabFM radio kit (https://www.sparkfun.com/products/11043) to create a working radio for your tree. There's enough space inside to accommodate the PCB and related electronics, and the speaker mounts into the hole (perhaps a little deathstar evocative, I'll admit). Just added the Studio 360 logo to the other side, working on opening up the radio controls as well, although the latter is difficult without the kit in front of me... Please let me know if you're interested in seeing more, will keep working on it!

PRINT WITH SUPPORT!!!  
Other than that - still a work in progress, but the pieces should snap together fine, with enough space to accomodate the PCB and electronics.  
Antenna and power should feed out the hole in the top where the hanger goes; would be interesting to try to power off of a christmas tree light!
